The activity attempts to influence factors such as locus of control, self-efficacy, outcome expectancies, and social norms, all of them known to be important mediators in the process of behavior change (Conner & Norman, 1996;
Rutter & Quine, 2002). Furthermore, the activity was based on educational principles such as emphasizing short term positive consequences of behavior (Maibach & Cotton, 1995), involving the students actively (Cooper & Scher, 1994). The design of the classroom program was based not only on careful examination of previous successful interventions but also on discussions of program elements with selected experts, careful adjustment to Norwegian conditions, collaboration with teachers, parents and students, and pretesting of the program at two secondary schools. The program was administered under conditions typical of most classrooms. When the intervention was planned, it was considered important to adjust it to everyday life at schools. With this in mind, elements suggested to be part of the classroom program were simplicity, well-known pedagogical methods, and demands for low-cost audio-visual equipment only.
The program has emphasized active involvement by the students in every session and it has been focused on non-smoking as a kind of freedom. Experiencing freedom and being actively involved probably appeals particularly well to high sensation seekers, and may represent a contrast to the traditional kinds of communication and teaching practices in schools.

